s a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds  aSponsored by EPA, Office of Research and Developmentb68-02-0242e1A2013g113 a"The report documents development, demonstration, and control now in progress in Japan on Japanese processes pertaining to NOx abatement from flue gases. It includes Japanese environmental emission and control standards, and measurement methods. It presents process descriptions, states of development, advantages, disadvantages, economics, and flow sheets for 13 processes (including combustion control, reduction, and adsorption) for NOx abatement from waste gases. A new type of burner seems most promising for combustion modification; catalytic reduction seems most promising for NOx removal from flue gases. NOx source contributions in the Tokyo Bay area are: 39% motor vehicles, 22% electricity generation, 31% industry, and 8% other sources."--Abstract.  aIncludes bibliographical references (leaf 37). 0aAtmospheric nitrogen oxideszJapan. 0aFlue gasesxPurificationxEquipment and supplies. 0aAir qualityxStandardszJapan. 0aAirxPollutionxStandardszJapan. 7aAirxPollutionxStandards.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00802166 7aAir qualityxStandards.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00802527 7aAtmospheric nitrogen oxides.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00820447 7aFlue gasesxPurificationxEquipment and supplies.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00927944 7aJapan.2fast0(OCoLC)fst012040821https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PBJkT7GyCmyjxytDfqk6Yfq1 aTohata, Heiichiro.1 aPrinciotta, Frank T.1 aUnited States.bEnvironmental Protection Agency.bOffice of Research and Monitoring.  ihas work:aNitrogen oxide abatement technology in Japan, 1973 (Text)1https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/entity/E39PCFPDXmPW48ddK4WqjRm8834https://id.oclc.org/worldcat/ontology/hasWork 0aEnvironmental Protection Service report series.  aC0bGPO  aHistoric Shelflist; Drawer 302; LAC56  aHistoric Shelflist Drawer 312; HSL003; 2026020402659cam a2